# Branded Type & Sensitive Data Rules

Defines a **two-tier brand pattern** for all typed values in the codebase. Both tiers are derived from a single source of truth at `src/common/types/brand.type.ts`.

- **`BrandedType`** — for data that is **unique** but not sensitive (e.g. `UserId`, `OrderId`, `PlayerId`)
- **`StrictDataType`** — extends `BrandedType` and adds `__isSensitiveData` marker for data that is **both unique and sensitive** (e.g. `HashedPassword`, `JwtToken`, `ApiKey`, `RefreshToken`)

> Sensitive data MUST NOT be declared as plain `BrandedType`. It MUST extend `StrictDataType` so that Logger / Mapper / Redactor can detect it via the `__isSensitiveData` marker.

---

## 1. Core Definitions

File: `src/common/types/brand.type.ts`

```typescript
// Tier 1: BrandedType — unique value, NOT sensitive
export type BrandedType<T, K extends string> = T & {
  readonly __brand: K;
};

// Tier 2: StrictDataType — unique AND sensitive
// Extends BrandedType and adds the __isSensitiveData discriminant marker
export type StrictDataType<T, K extends string> = BrandedType<T, K> & {
  readonly __isSensitiveData: true;
};

// Compile-time type guard only.
// Works at runtime ONLY when StrictDataType is a class wrapper (object with actual property).
// Does NOT work for primitive-based StrictDataType (string | number + `as` cast) —
// use SensitiveDataRedactor field-name pattern matching for runtime detection instead.
export const isSensitiveData = (data: unknown): data is StrictDataType<unknown, string> =>
  typeof data === 'object' && data !== null && (data as any).__isSensitiveData === true;
```

---

## 2. Decision Matrix

| Data characteristic                        | Type to use                 | Examples                                                        |
| ------------------------------------------ | --------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Unique identifier (not sensitive)          | `BrandedType<T, K>`         | `UserId`, `OrderId`, `PlayerId`, `ItemId`                       |
| Unique + Sensitive (leaking = security incident) | `StrictDataType<T, K>` | `HashedPassword`, `JwtToken`, `ApiKey`, `RefreshToken`, `OtpSecret` |
| Non-unique plain value                     | primitive                   | `displayName: string`, `quantity: number`                       |

**Rule of thumb:** If leaking this field into a log constitutes a security incident, it must be `StrictDataType`.

---

## 3. Declaring a `BrandedType` (Unique only)

File: `src/common/types/user-id.type.ts`

```typescript
import { BrandedType } from '@common/types/brand.type';

export type UserId = BrandedType<string, 'UserId'>;

export const isUserId = (value: unknown): value is UserId =>
  typeof value === 'string' && value.trim().length > 0;

export const toUserId = (value: string): UserId =>
  value.trim() as UserId;

export const toSafeUserId = (value: unknown): UserId | unknown =>
  isUserId(value) ? toUserId(value) : value;
```

---

## 4. Declaring a `StrictDataType` (Unique + Sensitive)

File: `src/common/types/hashed-password.type.ts`

```typescript
import { StrictDataType } from '@common/types/brand.type';

export type HashedPassword = StrictDataType<string, 'HashedPassword'>;

export const isHashedPassword = (value: unknown): value is HashedPassword =>
  typeof value === 'string' && value.length >= 60;

export const toHashedPassword = (value: string): HashedPassword =>
  value as HashedPassword;

export const toSafeHashedPassword = (value: unknown): HashedPassword | unknown =>
  isHashedPassword(value) ? toHashedPassword(value) : value;

export type ApiKey = StrictDataType<string, 'ApiKey'>;

export const isApiKey = (value: unknown): value is ApiKey =>
  typeof value === 'string' && value.trim().length >= 32;

export const toApiKey = (value: string): ApiKey =>
  value.trim() as ApiKey;

export const toSafeApiKey = (value: unknown): ApiKey | unknown =>
  isApiKey(value) ? toApiKey(value) : value;
```

`StrictDataType` inherits `__brand` from `BrandedType` — no need to redeclare it.

---

## 5. Implementation in DTO / Entity

```typescript
import { Transform } from 'class-transformer';
import { IsString, IsNotEmpty, MinLength } from 'class-validator';
import { UserId, toSafeUserId } from '@common/types/user-id.type';
import { ApiKey, toSafeApiKey } from '@common/types/api-key.type';

export class CreateOrderDto {
  // Tier 1: BrandedType at DTO boundary
  @IsString()
  @IsNotEmpty()
  @Transform(({ value }) => toSafeUserId(value))
  readonly userId!: UserId;

  // Tier 2: StrictDataType at DTO boundary
  @IsString()
  @MinLength(32)
  @Transform(({ value }) => toSafeApiKey(value))
  readonly apiKey!: ApiKey;
}
```

DTO transforms MUST convert valid values to BrandedType/StrictDataType at the boundary. Invalid values should remain unchanged so `class-validator` can return a validation error; transform helpers MUST NOT throw or return `CommonResponse`.

```typescript
const userId = dto.userId; // already UserId after ValidationPipe + @Transform
const apiKey = dto.apiKey; // already ApiKey after ValidationPipe + @Transform
```

```typescript
export class AdminEntity {
  constructor(
    public readonly id: AdminId,                   // Tier 1: BrandedType
    public username: string,                       // primitive (non-unique)
    private readonly passwordHash: HashedPassword, // Tier 2: StrictDataType
  ) {}
}
```

